Ingest_LDD.name: Clipper
Ingest_LDD.comment:
The Clipper dictionary contains classes that describe aspects of the Europa Clipper Orbiter mission and related instruments.
-T. Hare, Initial version 1.0.0.0 , (2023-07-20) provide initial generic mission attributes
-T.Hare, initial updates for SUDA (2023-15-11)
-Ray Espiritu (APL, 2023-11-29) added the following EIS keywords: filter_used nframes Detector_Region class containing: readout_start_row readout_end_row row_step_size readout_start_col readout_end_col row_time_padding row_offset tdi_rows modified the following EIS keywords: mode
-Ray Espiritu (APL, 2024-02-25) -added the following EIS keywords: Checkline_Row class containing: detector_row readout_order -deleted the following EIS keywords. These were placeholders from LROC and are not used by EIS: instrument_mode_id exposure_code lookup_table_type interframe_delay spacecraft_clock_preroll_count preroll_time dac_reset_level line_code line_exposure_code line_exposure_duration
-Ray Espiritu (APL, 2024-02-27) -added the following keywords: gain detector_temp fpm_temp1 fpm_temp2 frame_capture_start_count gimbal_alongtrack gimbal_crosstrack
-T.Hare (2024-03-04) - removed ETHEMIS until the team is ready to add attributes

DD_Attribute.name: mission_phase_name
DD_Attribute.definition: The mission_phase_name identifies a time period within the mission.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: This phase covers the time period prior to launch. This may be used to describe ground calibration files or data created prior to launch to support post-launch activities.
This phase includes include launch, initial acquisition, solar array deployment, establishment of power-positive attitude, and re-establishing telemetry.

This phase starts one day after launch and includes two sub-phases: Inner Cruise and Outer Cruise. Activity includes flight system characterization and navigating to the Mars and Earth gravity assists along with periodic maintenance, calibrations, and navigation activities.
This phase starts three months prior to JOI and includes two sub-phases: Jupiter Approach and Jupiter Orbit Capture. Activities include navigation maneuvers to achieve Jupiter orbit capture.

This phase starts eight hours after perijove and includes four sub-phases: Transition to Europa Campaign 1, Europa Campaign 1, Transition to Europa Campaign 2 and Europa Campaign 2. Activities include positioning for and execution of close flybys of Europa, Ganymede and Callisto.
This phase starts 30 days after the last targeted closest approach of Europa. Activities include preparation for impact with Jupiter.

DD_Attribute.name: spacecraft_clock_start_count
DD_Attribute.definition: The spacecraft_clock_start_count attribute provides the value of the spacecraft clock at the actual start of image acquisition. There may be small inconsistencies with start_date_time due to varying correlation between UTC and the spacecraft clock. For purposes of data analysis the spacecraft clock value should be used. The format of this field is compatible with the NAIF Toolkit software where s = seconds converted from the clock's coarse counter and m = seconds converted from the clock's fine counter.

DD_Attribute.name: spacecraft_clock_stop_count
DD_Attribute.definition: The spacecraft_clock_stop_count attribute provides the value of the spacecraft clock at the actual end of image acquisition. There may be small inconsistencies with stop_date_time due to varying correlation between UTC and the spacecraft clock. For purposes of data analysis the spacecraft clock value should be used. The format of this field is compatible with the NAIF Toolkit software where s = seconds converted from the clock's coarse counter and m = seconds converted from the clock's fine counter.

DD_Attribute.name: release_number
DD_Attribute.definition: Release_number is the number of a scheduled release of data from PDS. The first data release would be Release 1. The release_number for a given product is always the first release in which it appears, and does not change if the product is revised later.

DD_Attribute.name: orbit_number
DD_Attribute.definition: The orbit_number attribute identifies the number of the orbital revolution of the spacecraft around Jupiter. Prior to JOI (i.e., from launch through cruise including gravity assists), the orbit value will be 0. After JOI, starting with the first apojove, the value will increase by 1 with each revolution around Jupiter incrementing at each subsequent apojove.

DD_Attribute.name: encounter_id
DD_Attribute.definition: The Playback and Flyby periods together comprise an Encounter, defined as the period of time during the Tour beginning two days before the targeted closest approach of a Jovian moon, and ending two days before the next targeted closest approach of a Jovian moon. While most Jupiter orbits include a targeted flyby, there are some phasing orbits without a targeted flyby; in these cases, an encounter will span more than one orbit. Valid values consist of a three-character identifier (e.g., EO1, G02, etc.) where "E01" indicates the first encounter with Europa and "G02" indicates the second encounter with Ganymede and so on. There is one more additional special value of "XXX" representing data collected during cruise up until the first encounter.

DD_Attribute.name: aid
DD_Attribute.definition: A hexadecimal representation of the Accountability Identifier (AID) which serves as a globally unique identifier across all instruments and mission phases for an observational activity onboard the spacecraft. Data tagged with a given AID is collected into an Accountable Data Product (ADP) on the ground and will result in one or more associated PDS data products in the archive. The AID is a 32-bit unsigned integer which contains three fields: Instrument ID (4-bits), Orbit Number (9-bits) and Data Acquisition ID (19-bits). The hexadecimal string value is prefixed with “0x”.

DD_Attribute.name: producer_institution_name
DD_Attribute.definition: The producer_institution_name attribute identifies a university, research center, NASA center, or other institution associated with the production of a data product.

DD_Attribute.name: product_type
DD_Attribute.definition: The product_type attribute indicates the processing level of an individual data product.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: Original data from an instrument. If compression, reformatting, packetization, or other translation has been applied to facilitate data transmission or storage, those processes will be reversed so that the archived data are in a PDS approved archive format.
Data that have been processed beyond the raw level but which have not yet reached calibrated status.
Data converted to physical units, which makes values independent of the instrument.

Results that have been distilled from one or more calibrated data products (for example, maps, gravity or magnetic fields, or ring particle size distributions). Supplementary data, such as calibration tables or tables of viewing geometry, used to interpret observational data should also be classified as "derived" data if not easily matched to one of the other categories.

DD_Attribute.name: product_version_id
DD_Attribute.definition: The product_version_id attribute identifies the version of an individual data product.

DD_Attribute.name: rationale_desc
DD_Attribute.definition: The rationale_desc attribute describes the rationale for performing a particular observation.

DD_Attribute.name: data_quality_desc
DD_Attribute.definition: The data_quality_desc attribute describes the data qualities associated with a data_quality_id attribute.

DD_Attribute.name: data_quality_id
DD_Attribute.definition: The data_quality_id attribute provides a numeric key which identifies the quality of data available for a particular time period. The data_quality_id scheme is unique to a given instrument and is described by the associated data_quality_desc attribute.

DD_Attribute.name: upload_id
DD_Attribute.definition: The upload_id attribute describes a spacecraft command set that is associated with the given data product.

DD_Attribute.name: flight_software_version_id
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates version of instrument flight software used to acquire image. For example, "1.00".

DD_Attribute.name: command_sequence_number
DD_Attribute.definition: Numeric identifier for the sequence of commands sent to the spacecraft which include this image.

DD_Attribute.name: image_id
DD_Attribute.definition: Numeric identifier for this image within the onboard command sequence.

DD_Attribute.name: detector_row
DD_Attribute.definition: Part of the Checkline_Row class. Identifies the detector row used in the checkline image. This row is readout multiple times in a checklines image and is used for jitter correction.

DD_Attribute.name: mode
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates whether the EIS detector was commanded to take images in framing or pushbroom mode.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: EIS commanded to take images in framing mode.
EIS commanded to take images in pushbroom mode.

DD_Attribute.name: compression_flag
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates if lossless compression was commanded (0=no, 1=yes)

DD_Attribute.name: frame_capture_start_count
DD_Attribute.definition: timestamp of the EIS Digital board (DB) receipt of the first detector line read out for a given frame. The detector can read out lines from multiple colors in the same frame and send each color to a separate TDI collection in memory where each TDI collection is associated with a unique AID. However, each AID packet will have the same frame_capture_start_count for a given frame. Thus, need this value to derive the actual starttime for a given TDI row.

DD_Attribute.name: filter_used
DD_Attribute.definition: Indicates the region of the detector that was used to generate an EIS image. This includes the clear and color stripe filters as well as the clear framing area of the detector.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: Clear filter region of the detector.
One micron filter region of the detector.
IR 1 filter region of the detector.
Red filter region of the detector.
Green filter region of the detector.
Blue filter region of the detector.
Near UV filter region of the detector.
Panchromatic framing area region of the detector.
Masked region of the detector.

DD_Attribute.name: gain
DD_Attribute.definition: Gain state of the EIS detector when the image was taken.

DD_Permissible_Value.value_meaning: EIS in high gain state.
EIS in low gain state.

DD_Attribute.name: gimbal_alongtrack
DD_Attribute.definition: Gimbal motor position in steps in the along-track direction of spacecraft motion. This is measured as an offset from the "home" position. 0.046875 degrees per step.

DD_Attribute.name: gimbal_crosstrack
DD_Attribute.definition: Gimbal motor position in steps in the cross-track direction of spacecraft motion. This is measured as an offset from the "home" position. 0.046875 degrees per step.

DD_Attribute.name: nframes
DD_Attribute.definition: Records the commanded number of frames for an EIS observation. A single observation may consist of multiple images with the same detector settings, therefore number of frames collected may not necessarily correlate to the number of rows in the image.

DD_Attribute.name: readout_order
DD_Attribute.definition: Part of the Checkline_Row class. Provides an ordering of the detector rows that are used to generate the checklines image. The Checkline_Row with the lowest valued readout_order is read first, followed by the next higher readout_order, and so on. After the Checkline_Row with the highest valued readout_order is read out the instrument goes back to the lowest valued readout_order.

DD_Attribute.name: readout_start_row
DD_Attribute.definition: For a framing image this is the starting row of the detector to be read out, For a TDI image this is the start of the TDI rows to be summed together.

DD_Attribute.name: readout_end_row
DD_Attribute.definition: For a framing image this is the end row of the detector to be read out, For a TDI image this is the end row of the TDI rows to be summed together.

DD_Attribute.name: row_step_size
DD_Attribute.definition: Row increment step size when reading from readout_start_row to readout_end_row. For a step size of 1 the detector rows are contiguous. For a step size of 2 the detector skips the readout of every other row. The value can be negative in which case the readout_start_row must be greater than the readout_end_row. The step size will be inclusive of the readout_end_row. For example, if the readout_start_row is 1 and readout_end_row is 5 and row_step_size is 2 then the rows read out are 1, 3, 5.

DD_Attribute.name: readout_start_col
DD_Attribute.definition: The EIS detector can be commanded to read out portions of the detector in pre-defined 256 column sections known as ports. This keyword defines the starting column of the detector to be read out. Index starts at column 0 and ends at column 4095. All rows in a given EIS image will start at this column in the detector.

DD_Attribute.name: readout_end_col
DD_Attribute.definition: The EIS detector can be commanded to read out portions of the detector in pre-defined 256 column sections known as ports. This keyword defines the ending column of the detector to be read out. Index starts at column 0 and ends at column 4095. All rows in a given EIS image will end at this column in the detector.

DD_Attribute.name: row_time_padding
DD_Attribute.definition: Additional time that the detector readout state machine will wait before moving to the next line. This value affects image exposure time.

DD_Attribute.name: row_offset
DD_Attribute.definition: Number of readout rows to wait before reading out a given row to refresh the accumulation of photons on a given row in the detector. This allows for shorter exposure times than would normally occur if the detector waits until all rows are read out once before refreshing a given row. This value affects image exposure time.

DD_Attribute.name: tdi_rows
DD_Attribute.definition: Number of detector rows added together by the DPU in order to perform digital time delay integration, resulting in one TDI row in the output image.

DD_Attribute.name: spacecraft_clock_count_partition
DD_Attribute.definition: The spacecraft_clock_count_partition attribute indicates the clock partition active for the spacecraft_clock_start_count and spacecraft_clock_stop_count attributes.

DD_Attribute.name: event_count
DD_Attribute.definition: Number of events contained within a given AID.

DD_Attribute.name: epoch
DD_Attribute.definition: Epoch defining the zero point of relative times in year month day UTC. For example: "YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss.ssssssZ"

DD_Attribute.name: start_time
DD_Attribute.definition: Milliseconds of the first event within this AID (time in milliseconds since epoch).

DD_Attribute.name: end_time
DD_Attribute.definition: Milliseconds of the last event within this AID (time in milliseconds since epoch).

DD_Attribute.name: event_id
DD_Attribute.definition: Event-specific event identifier from the FPGA Header.

DD_Attribute.name: event_time
DD_Attribute.definition: FPGA event time (time of event trigger in milliseconds since epoch).

DD_Attribute.name: category
DD_Attribute.definition: Category determined by Flight Software Processing.

DD_Attribute.name: tof_peak_count
DD_Attribute.definition: Total number of TOF peaks found.

DD_Attribute.name: tof_mean
DD_Attribute.definition: Selected TOF waveform mean.

DD_Attribute.name: tof_var
DD_Attribute.definition: Signal to Noise ratio squared of selected TOF waveform.

DD_Attribute.name: qv_max_amplitude
DD_Attribute.definition: Maximum amplitude (raw value) for velocity waveform (QV).

DD_Attribute.name: qv_mean
DD_Attribute.definition: Mean of selected velocity waveform data (QV).

DD_Attribute.name: qv_var
DD_Attribute.definition: Signal to Noise ratio squared for velocity waveform (QV).

DD_Attribute.name: qt_max_amplitude
DD_Attribute.definition: Maximum amplitude (raw value) for target waveform (QT).

DD_Attribute.name: qt_mean
DD_Attribute.definition: Mean of selected target data (QT).

DD_Attribute.name: qt_var
DD_Attribute.definition: Signal to Noise ratio squared for target (QT).

DD_Attribute.name: qi_max_amplitude
DD_Attribute.definition: Maximum amplitude (raw value) for ion waveform (QI).

DD_Attribute.name: qi_mean
DD_Attribute.definition: Mean of selected ion data (QI).

DD_Attribute.name: qi_var
DD_Attribute.definition: Signal to Noise ratio squared for ion data (QI).

DD_Class.name: Observation_Information
DD_Class.definition: The Observation_Information class provides information about a science observation.

DD_Class.name: EIS_Parameters
DD_Class.definition: The class contains all the instrument specific attributes for the EIS WAC and NAC.

DD_Class.name: Detector_Region
DD_Class.definition: The class contains the start/end readout rows, start/end readout columns, and row step size describing the region of the detector that is contained in an EIS image. For example, raw masked row images, where the top and bottom regions of the detector are read out in a single framing image. One instance of this object should be provided for each region that is contained in the image.

DD_Class.name: Checkline_Row
DD_Class.definition: Defines the detector row and readout order for a checklines image. A Checkline_Row class is created for every detector row used as a checkline. For example, if there were 3 checklines readout for a given checklines image then this class would appear three times in the framing image label to define each checklines row. This class does NOT appear in the label for the checklines image. Instead there is a Detector_Region class for each checkline.

DD_Class.name: SUDA_Parameters
DD_Class.definition: The class contains all the instrument specific attributes for the SUDA instrument.

DD_Class.name: SUDA_Event
DD_Class.definition: The class contains all the events for SUDA instrument.

DD_Rule_Statement.rule_message: clipper:error:sclk_rule_0: If clipper:spacecraft_clock_start_count and clipper:spacecraft_clock_stop_count are present, they must begin with a partition number followed by a forward slash, OR the partition number must be given by clipper:spacecraft_clock_count_partition.
DD_Rule_Statement.rule_description: If spacecraft_clock_start_count and spacecraft_clock_stop_count are present, they must begin with a partition number followed by a forward slash, OR the partition number must be given by spacecraft_clock_count_partition.
